Egypt inaugurates first freely elected president
Muhammad Morsi has been sworn in, but his triumphant day is unlikely to end Egypt&#39;s political unrest.
ISLAMIST Muhammad Morsi promised a &quot;new Egypt&quot; when he was inaugurated as the country&#39;s first freely elected president since Hosni Mubarak, who was ousted 16 months earlier.
With his inauguration before the Supreme Constitutional Court, Morsi also became the first freely elected Islamic president in the Arab world and Egypt&#39;s fifth head of state since the monarchy was overthrown some 60 years ago.
He was sworn in before 18 black-robed judges in a mansion built overlooking the Nile that resembles an ancient Egyptian temple.
&quot;We strive for a better tomorrow, a new Egypt and a second republic,&quot; Morsi said in a ceremony broadcast live on state television.
&quot;Today the Egyptian people have laid the foundation for a new life - absolute freedom, true democracy and stability,&quot; said Morsi, a 60-year-old US-educated engineer and member of the Muslim Brotherhood, a fundamentalist group that has been the target of fierce attacks by individual governments.
When Morsi arrived in a small motorcade shortly after 11 a.m. local time, hundreds of soldiers and police were guarding the building.
Only a few hundred supporters gathered outside the courthouse to celebrate the president, and unlike the presidential pageantry of the Mubarak era, traffic was only stopped briefly to allow the motorcade to pass through the usually busy road connecting the city center with the suburbs to the south.
The personal prestige of Morsi, mockingly described as the uncharismatic &quot;spare tire&quot; of the Muslim Brotherhood, has soared since his victory and his speech on Friday, which aimed to present him not only as the candidate of Islamists, but also of all those who want to see an end to the rebellion against the authoritarian Mubarak .
&quot;Egypt today is a civil, national, constitutional and modern state,&quot; Morsi, dressed in a blue business suit with a red tie, told judges in the wood-paneled chamber where he was sworn in.
Morsi later traveled to Cairo University, where he was to deliver an inaugural address.
While standing at attention, he received an official welcome from a military band that played the national anthem.
The military commander, Field Marshal Husayn Tantáví, was present.
His arrival was accompanied by chants of &quot;the army and the people are one hand&quot; from hundreds of people gathered in the university&#39;s main lecture hall.
Cairo University was founded in 1908 as a center of secular education and later became a stronghold of Islamic student movements in the 1970s.
Morsi took a symbolic oath on Friday in Tahrir Square, the birthplace of the revolution that ended Mubarak&#39;s authoritarian rule last year, and solemnly vowed to retake the presidential powers stripped from his office by a military council that took over from the ousted leader.
But by agreeing to take the official oath in court, rather than parliament as is customary, he bowed to the will of the military, suggesting the power struggle will continue.
Morsi&#39;s speech in Tahrir Square was full of dramatic populist gestures.
