Today I feel like I have become a hoarder.
I haven&#39;t seen candy in my apartment for two years, and this year probably won&#39;t be any different.
However, statistics show that I am the black sheep when it comes to Halloween.
According to the National Retail Federation (NRF), most Americans will celebrate Halloween this year – 158 million of them, in fact – and will spend a total of $6.9 billion on candy, costumes and decorations.
But what I always look forward to on Halloween are the trends.
According to the NRF, of the $6.9 billion spent, $1.2 billion is expected to go to costumes.
This year, sexy inanimate objects are the latest fashion fad.
Sexy doesn&#39;t just have to be women anymore; foods like pizza, hamburger and carrots can be sexy too.
As for the men, I expect we&#39;ll see a lot of zombies thanks to the parade of the dead, and I bet Daft Punk&#39;s spacemen will make it to our Instagram feeds this year.
According to Google, the most searched costumes are zombies, Batman, pirates and witches.
I suppose there&#39;s nothing wrong with going with tradition.
Last year we dressed our dogs in costumes and to my surprise we were not the only ones.
In fact, Americans will spend $330 million on pet costumes this year, according to the NRF.
So you will see a lot of funny dogs.
When it comes to sweets, we waste no time.
According to Nielsen, Americans will spend $1.9 billion.
That&#39;s roughly 300 million kg of Hershey bars, lollipops, Milk Duds and Twizzlers, and Clark bars.
That&#39;s amazing news for the 41 million carolers who, according to the U.S. Department of Commerce, are about to invade our neighborhoods.
In fact, we buy, and believe it or not, 45 million kg of chocolate during Halloween.
The one thing we don&#39;t want is candy corn, and yet, according to the National Candy Stores Association, nearly 16,000 tons of them are sold around Halloween.
That&#39;s about 9 billion individual candy corns.
That&#39;s a mystery I&#39;ve never solved.
Nothing is more typical of Halloween than haunted houses.
They have the best names, like &quot;Terror behind the walls&quot;, &quot;Howl-O-Scream&quot; and &quot;The house of shock&quot;.
In fact, there are 1,200 officially dedicated haunted houses in the United States that, according to the American Haunted Houses Society, generate $500 million in revenue, and that includes those awesome pictures of you peed on by the scares that your friend posts on Facebook and you can&#39;t delete them and the person you like will view the photo and add a comment like &quot;you look nice&quot;.
And finally, a little about pumpkins.
Charlie Brown introduced us to the Great Pumpkin when we were little, and carving a pumpkin lantern is like decorating a Christmas tree - we&#39;ve been doing it since we were little.
Luckily for us, the pumpkin baby trend only started last year thanks to Pinterest, so most of us grew up carving a pumpkin instead of sitting in one.
This year, according to the U.S. Census Bureau, Americans will spend about $106 million on pumpkins.
The pumpkin lantern with a flickering flame on your front porch probably came from Illinois, where 245,000 tons of pumpkins were grown this year.
If you&#39;re looking for something extra, call Tim and Susan Mathisdon of Napa, California, and try carving their nearly one-ton pumpkin.
