A US-Mexico drug-smuggling tunnel with its own railroad has been found
One of the most sophisticated drug-smuggling tunnels between the US and Mexico has been discovered, complete with its own lighting, ventilation and electric railway.
US authorities have described the roughly one meter by one meter tunnel as one of the most sophisticated secret passages they have ever discovered.
The tunnel, which winds for the length of nearly six football fields, connects warehouses near Tijuana, Mexico, and San Diego, USA.
The area is full of nondescript warehouses where trucks can be easily hidden before they are loaded with drugs.
Authorities said the tunnel was closed before drugs could be smuggled through it.
Along with the discovery of the tunnel, authorities also seized eight and a half tons of marijuana and about 150 kilograms of cocaine, according to court records.
The three men, who authorities say worked as drivers, were charged with possession with intent to distribute marijuana and cocaine.
If convicted, he faces prison terms ranging from 10 years to life in prison.
In the city of Nogales, Arizona, smugglers penetrate extensive drainage channels.
The tunnel is the eighth largest corridor discovered in San Diego since 2006.
Some of the largest tunnels were discovered in October after the marijuana harvest in central Mexico, which poses a challenge for drug cartels to get their product to consumers as quickly as possible.
In 2010, authorities found a 2,000-foot-long corridor equipped with rails that led from the kitchen of a house in Tijuana to two warehouses in San Diego.
Is Europe&#39;s elite ready to trade with Britain?
The Business for Britain campaign was launched in April with a promise to bring businesses together and define what changes to the relationship with the EU British businesses and job-creating companies want to see.
To do this, we commissioned the largest and most comprehensive survey, asking leading UK business people their views on Britain, trade and the EU.
YouGov interviewed 1,000 business leaders representing UK businesses of all sizes and across sectors and regions.
The results of the survey will come as a surprise to many.
We found that the vast majority of businesses are now looking to export outside of Europe, focusing on countries that are modernizing and growing, while EU states are stagnating.
They want to see the government prioritize new trade links with countries such as China, India and Brazil, rather than getting bogged down in the long and arduous process of reforming Europe&#39;s arcane institutions.
When asked for their views on specific policy areas – from monopoly regulation to product laws – most business people expressed the view that control of these key powers should return to Westminster.
There was general dissatisfaction with the single market, and business people said the costs of Brussels regulations now outweighed the benefits of being part of the European trading area – with even 40 percent of large businesses, traditionally the most pro-European companies, agreeing.
And finally, our survey of business leaders revealed the most telling finding: a clear majority want Britain to seek a treaty change and relationship with the EU that should be based on trade, not politics.
The findings, which were agreed by businesses of all sizes and major business groups, show that the business sector is pushing for &quot;meaningful change&quot; that will bring influence back to Britain.
The stakes are high – achieving a treaty change and a better deal for Britain could mean a gain of up to 16% in the referendum vote to remain in the EU.
The Prime Minister should not hesitate: this poll shows British business backs his plan to amend the terms of Britain&#39;s EU membership.
It also shows that the business sector expects this amendment to represent a significant shift away from the current balance of power back towards Britain.
A better deal for Britain is possible and increasingly necessary as the eurozone moves towards closer economic and fiscal union.
Jobs and growth in Britain must be the priority, and as our survey results show, for business this means a refocus on trade and a fundamental change in Brussels&#39; regulatory approach.
