Frontier Airlines is about to charge for carry-on bags
Frontier Airlines plans to charge up to $100 for carry-on baggage on its flights.
Frontier Airlines plans to introduce a fee of up to $100 per carry-on bag and $2 per coffee or soda, though it said in its announcement Wednesday that passengers will be able to keep the entire can.
The new hand luggage charge applies to luggage in the overhead bin, so small bags under the seat will continue to be free.
Frontier says it will charge $25 if the fee is paid in advance and $100 if passengers wait until arriving at the gate to pay.
Frontier spokeswoman Kate O&#39;Malley said the $100 fee is intended to encourage passengers to pay in advance.
&quot;We would hate to collect that fee,&quot; she said.
Airlines began charging for first and second checked bags in 2008.
Passengers tried to avoid these fees by cramming as much as they could into carry-on bags hidden in the storage area, so there was often a lack of space in this area.
Fees are one way to teach passengers to bring less stuff on board.
O&#39;Malley said the new fee isn&#39;t really about raising more money.
The thing is, Frontier&#39;s most loyal customers have made it abundantly clear that finding space in the overhead storage is becoming more and more difficult.
Passengers who purchase tickets on the company&#39;s website will not pay.
This means that one passenger in line at Frontier&#39;s gate can bring a bag for which they pay nothing, while another passenger in line pays $100 for the same bag.
O&#39;Malley said the website and check-in procedures will be adjusted to ensure passengers are aware of the fee before they arrive at the gate.
Frontier&#39;s new carry-on fee won&#39;t go into effect until the summer, but a date has yet to be set.
Passengers often complain about baggage fees and other fees, but airlines love them.
They argue that baggage handling costs money and passengers who request the service should pay for it.
Many on Wall Street see the additional baggage fee as a sign that airlines are struggling to raise enough cash to cover the cost of air traffic after years of losses.
But the majority did not touch the hand luggage fees.
Spirit Airlines was the first to charge for carry-on bags three years ago, and fellow low-cost carrier Allegiant Air later followed suit.
Hungary&#39;s Wizz Air is the only company that also has such charges, says aviation consultant Jay Sorensen, who closely monitors the surcharges.
In a December 2011 report, he estimated Spirit&#39;s carry-on fee would generate $50 million annually.
Sorensen, a former Midwest Airlines executive, recently flew with Spirit and marveled at what he saw at the gate when passengers were met with Spirit&#39;s unusual carry-on fee.
&quot;Boarding the plane was the smoothest I&#39;ve ever seen in my aviation career,&quot; he said.
I expected to see gnashing of teeth and arguments at the gate.
The plane was full, he said, &quot;and boarding was a snap.&quot;
Frontier will also apply fees for coffee, tea, soda and juice, following Spirit&#39;s lead.
Frontier said passengers who get soda or juice can keep the entire can and the coffee will be refilled for free.
Water will continue to be served free of charge.
US Airways briefly tried to introduce beverage charges in 2008, but backed off seven months later after complaints from passengers, and no other major airline has followed suit.
Frontier&#39;s latest move to charge a carry-on bag unless passengers purchase a flight directly from the airline is its latest effort to drive customers directly to its website.
Airlines pay online travel sellers like Orbitz between $10 and $25 for each ticket sold.
This gave all the airlines an incentive to drive passengers to buy directly from them instead of through online travel agencies.
However, Frontier has gone the furthest in this area.
In September, it began giving customers who bought through an online travel agency just half their loyalty program miles.
On Wednesday, it cut the rewards for miles flown to 25 percent of the miles of a given trip.
So a 1,000-mile Frontier trip purchased through an online travel agency earns a 250-mile reward.
The company also allows customers to select their seat in advance only if they make the purchase directly through Frontier&#39;s website.
Frontier has a loyal customer base in its hometown of Denver, but its business is beginning to shrink and it&#39;s losing money.
Revenue fell 9 percent and capacity shrank nearly 13 percent in the first quarter, according to financial results reported Wednesday by corporate partner Republic Airways Holdings
Republic is trying to solve Frontier&#39;s financial problems by selling this airline.
