In November of last year, the analysis captured over 11,000 advertisements offering a job, of which 4,300 were published in the daily press and 6,800 advertisements (62 percent) on the Internet.
The Internet is therefore becoming the most important medium for posting job offers.
Back in 2005, when the survey was conducted for the first time, its share was 26 percent.
In the last two surveys (2007, 2010), it stabilized at around 60 percent.
According to the analysis, the advertisement of job opportunities largely reflects the current situation on the labor market.
An example can be a simple comparison of the number of published advertisements in a period of economic prosperity and in a time of economic crisis.
For example, in 2007, almost 25,900 advertisements were published in the same monitored period, in 2012 it was less than half.
The offer of jobs on the Internet is oriented towards a narrower, especially more qualified group of professions.
In contrast, the job offer in the daily press covers a wider spectrum of professions, including blue-collar ones, said the author of the analysis, Pavlína Šťastnová.
The degree of representation of selected professional groups is different for both media.
Advertisements looking for managers and executives, sales representatives, programmers and financial experts took the leading places on the Internet.
The position of programmers or managers of small businesses appeared only on the Internet.
In the daily press, the share of these professional professions is significantly lower, on the contrary, a large representation belongs mainly to service and blue-collar professions.
Of course, education is among the most frequently stated requirements that employers express through advertising offers.
Other monitored areas included knowledge of foreign languages, especially English.
In the daily press, the requirement to know a foreign language was stated in three percent of advertisements, on the Internet in 37 percent.
In only two percent of advertisements, employers required active knowledge of two foreign languages.
Claims for &#39;computer literacy&#39; appeared in 40 percent of advertisements (in the daily press in 11 percent, on the Internet in 57 percent).
Experience in the field was required in 54 percent of the advertisements.
Practice requirements are generally associated with qualified professions.
These are mainly production managers and other managers.
The blue-collar professions are mainly mechanics and repairmen or manufacturers and processors of food products or repairmen of electrical devices, added the author of the study, Jiří Tillner.
Employers also state requirements for the qualities and skills of potential applicants in half of their advertisements.
As the most frequently requested skills, communication skills have been appearing in first place in advertising for a long time.
Furthermore, employers demand flexibility, adaptability and dynamism, independence, responsibility, organizational skills and reliability.
