Black box in your car?
As America&#39;s road planners scramble to find money to fix the crumbling highway network, many are beginning to see a solution in a little black box that fits easily on your car&#39;s dashboard.
The devices, which track every mile a motorist drives and relay that information to authorities, are at the heart of a controversial effort by Washington and state planning officials to overhaul America&#39;s antiquated highway funding system.
The usually dull design of highways suddenly stimulated an intense debate and the formation of various associations.
Libertarians got together with environmental groups and lobbied for the government to use these little boxes that would record the miles you drive and maybe even where you drive—and then use that information to compile a tax assessment.
The Tea Party is horrified.
The American Civil Liberties Union is also deeply concerned and has cited a number of privacy concerns.
And while Congress can&#39;t agree on whether to proceed, some states are waiting for nothing.
They are looking at how they can move to a system where drivers pay per kilometer of road they drive over the next decade.
Thousands of motorists have already taken the black boxes, some of which have GPS tracking, for testing.
This is a real necessity for our nation.
&quot;It&#39;s not an issue where we have a lot of choice,&quot; said Hasan Ikhrata, executive director of the Southern California Association of State Governments, which plans for the state to begin tracking the mileage of every California motorist by 2025.
The way we pay these taxes will change.
This technology is used for this.
The stimulus is the fact that the Highway Trust Fund, funded by taxes Americans pay at gas stations, is at rock bottom.
Americans aren&#39;t buying as much gasoline as they used to.
Cars get a lot more mileage per gallon.
The federal tax alone, at 18.4 cents per gallon, has not increased in 20 years.
Due to the current high price of gasoline, politicians are reluctant to raise the tax by even a single penny.
&quot;A gas tax is simply not sustainable,&quot; said Lee Munnich, a transportation policy expert at the University of Minnesota.
His state recently put tracking devices in 500 cars to test this pay-per-mile system.
&quot;In the long run, it seems like the most logical alternative,&quot; he said.
Experts call it a mileage user fee.
It&#39;s no surprise that urban liberals like the idea, as taxes can be used to change driver behavior patterns, which can help reduce traffic congestion and greenhouse gas emissions, for example.
California planners look to this system as they plan strategies to meet the goals set forth in ambitious global warming laws.
But Republican Bill Shuster (D-Pennsylvania), chairman of the Transportation Committee, said he also sees it as the most workable long-term alternative.
Free-market advocates at the Reason Foundation also favor the idea of drivers paying for miles driven.
&quot;It&#39;s not a tax that&#39;s going to disappear into a black hole,&quot; said Adrian Moore, vice president of strategy at Reason.
People pay directly for what they get.
The initiative is also supported by two former US Secretary of Transportation, who in 2011 encouraged Congress to move in the direction of paying per kilometer.
The U.S. Senate last year approved a $90 million pilot project that would include about 10,000 cars.
But the House of Representatives leadership rejected the proposal, doing so because of the concerns of rural lawmakers representing constituents whose daily lives often involve traveling many miles to work outside the city.
However, several states and cities are still moving forward on their own.
The most zealous is Oregon, which has included 5,000 drivers in the nation&#39;s largest experiment.
These drivers will soon start paying the state a mileage tax, instead of a gas tax.
Nevada has already completed a pilot project.
New York is currently exploring the project.
Illinois is trying to do this on a limited basis for trucks.
