However, this concept does not only have supporters.
In Nevada, where about 50 volunteer cars were recently equipped with the device, drivers were concerned that the government was able to track their every move.
&quot;Concerns about Big Brother surveillance and things like that have been a big issue,&quot; said Alauddin Khan, who heads strategy and operations management at the Nevada Department of Transportation.
It wasn&#39;t something people wanted.
As the test project continued, the American Civil Liberties Union of Nevada warned on its website: &quot;It would be very easy to turn these devices into full-fledged surveillance devices.&quot;
