Nevada is among several states trying to find affordable technology that would allow the state to track how many miles a car drives, but not exactly when and where.
If you can do that, Khan said, the public will be calmer.
The hunt for such technology led some state agencies to a small company in California called True Mileage.
This company was not originally involved in the action to help the government in taxing drivers.
It wanted to break into the emerging liability insurance market, where drivers would pay based on how far they drove.
But the device he&#39;s testing is attracting the attention of road network planners because it doesn&#39;t use GPS and only delivers a limited amount of information, which is regularly uploaded via modem.
