For 21 years, Georges Bwelle watched his father pass out again and again, going to hospitals that were not equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaounde, the capital of Cameroon.
At first he was only treated for a broken arm, but then he developed an infection that spread to his brain, forming a hematoma there that troubled him throughout his life.
&quot;There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,&quot; says Georges Bwelle.
We would have to take him outside of Cameroon if we had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years transporting his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals where he received whatever treatment was simply available.
&quot;It&#39;s not easy,&quot; says Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five in the morning, rush to the hospital to be the first there, but you are not the first.
There are many patients.
Some people die just because they have to wait.
Since 2002, when Bwelle&#39;s father died, the situation has not changed much.
According to the World Health Organization, there is only one doctor per 5,000 inhabitants in Cameroon.
Just for comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor per 413 residents.
And even if Cameroonians could see a doctor, many would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and nearly three-quarters of healthcare spending in this country is private.
&quot;The only problem they have is poverty,&quot; says Bwelle.
S because of poverty they cannot enjoy life.
When Bwelle saw his father and many of his countrymen suffer, he decided to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his team of volunteers performed 700 surgeries for free last year.
He himself became a vascular surgeon at Yaounde Central Hospital.
And he founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, whose members visit rural areas on weekends to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he has helped almost 32,000 people with his group of volunteers.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others pile into vans, attach medical supplies to the roofs, and travel over rugged terrain to villages in need.
They are not always lucky.
More than once the vehicles have to push through the river and mud.
But when they arrive, they receive a true hero&#39;s welcome: feasting, singing and dancing, and the best lodging the community has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is truly a cause for celebration, and Bwelle – with his big smile and unbridled energy – is more than willing to join in the local merriment.
The next day, the team begins treating hundreds of patients.
&quot;We have 500 patients on each expedition,&quot; says Bwelle.
They come to the village from a radius of 60 kilometers, on foot.
During each of these weekends, doctors provide different medical assistance.
Many are being treated for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasitic diseases and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches or donated glasses or a free birth certificate – a document required by the school but which many impoverished families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations under local anesthesia.
The operations are usually done in the school building, the town hall or at home; after surgery, the patient gets up and goes to the recovery area to make room for the next patient.
With the help of light from a generator, an operating room and sanitary equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until the early hours of the morning.
It&#39;s exhausting, but the village musicians usually keep the team motivated.
&quot;They play drums all night long to keep us awake and keep working,&quot; says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team heads back to town, tired but proud of their work.
The group – made up of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – performed 700 surgeries for free last year and realizes that their help can mean a lot to local residents.
One man said he would be able to work again after hernia surgery.
&quot;This will change the future of our family,&quot; the man said.
In addition to organizing these weekend clinics and working as a surgeon at Bwelle Hospital, he also works at night for private health clinics around the city of Yaounde.
He says that this second job funds about 60% of his non-profit activities; private contributions cover the rest.
&quot;I&#39;m not sure when he actually sleeps,&quot; says Katie O&#39;Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia who volunteers for Bwelle&#39;s group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization to do these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students like O&#39;Malley, who come from the United States or Europe to join Bwelle on his mission, it&#39;s great practice they wouldn&#39;t get at home.
&quot;We washed Dr. Bwelle&#39;s hands thoroughly and removed blood stains or held instruments for him,&quot; says O&#39;Malley.
You never get to experience that as a second year medical student in America.
Student volunteers usually pay their own way to Cameroon and often arrive with donated medical supplies.
But once they arrive in Yaounde, Bwelle provides them with food, transport and studies.
&quot;He&#39;s a hero without a doubt,&quot; says O&#39;Malley.
He gives his life to this organization and his desire to help the people of Cameroon is endless.
For Bwelle, the constant sleigh is not a burden.
Helping others live happier lives, fulfilling the promise he made to his father, is something that brings him great joy.
&quot;I&#39;m so happy doing this job,&quot; says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope they see what I&#39;m doing.
To make people laugh, to ease their pain - that&#39;s why I do it.
