As the middle class impoverishes, Singapore&#39;s pawnshops are booming
At a pawnshop in Singapore&#39;s Bendemeer Mall, Janani Amirthalinga pawns a gold bracelet, ring and earrings to pay her daughter&#39;s school fees.
&quot;My husband and I just bought a house and I put all my money into it,&quot; says Ms Amirthalinga.
Although she receives $2,400 (SGD 3,000) as an administrator every month and her husband also works, the family&#39;s monthly income is insufficient, she says.
Indeed, demand across regions in Southeast Asia - where household debt is rising - is such that ValueMax, where the woman is carrying out her transaction, became the third-ranked pawnbroker on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
Jewelery pawning is not only a quick way to borrow cash – SGD 1,300 in Ms Amirthalinga&#39;s case – but it is also almost as cheap as unsecured bank loans.
Pawn shops in Singapore normally charge an annual percentage rate of 17 percent, just above the 15.4 percent rate offered by United Overseas Bank, a local bank with a branch in the same mall.
However, pawnshops have the advantage that they do not require verification of a person (payment history) or proof of income and can provide a loan faster than banks.
And so, as families feel the pressure from rising living costs and rising household and consumer debt, millions of people across the region are turning to pawnshops.
After five years of strong growth since the global financial crisis and cheap credit supported by loose monetary policy in advanced economies, low- and middle-income families are turning to pawnshops to deal with their worsening financial situation.
This week, rating agency Standard &amp; Poor&#39;s cited rising household credit use, largely due to rising rents, as a risk factor for the creditworthiness of Asian banks.
She said Malaysia, Thailand and Singapore have the highest household debt in Asia as a percentage of gross domestic product.
Malaysia tops the list at 80 percent of GDP, up from 60 percent in 2008.
Economists were also concerned about high levels of consumer debt in Thailand, which just barely emerged from a technical recession this week.
On Thursday, data showed continued weak exports and weakening consumer demand.
&quot;The bottom line is that with rising costs, people in the middle to low [income scale] will try to supplement their income wherever they can,&quot; said Song Seng Wun, an economist at Malaysia&#39;s CIMB Bank.
Historically high gold prices over the past two years have seen people rush to mortgage their personal assets and seize the opportunity to cash in their family jewels.
About 70 percent of the items pawned in the city&#39;s 200 pawnshops are gold.
People say: the price of gold looks good, we will stop grandma&#39;s gold necklace and get it back next month.
Thailand&#39;s largest pawn shop operator, EasyMoney, has seen up to a 20 percent increase in the number of customers using its pawn shops in recent months.
Growth in the mortgage industry is so great that ValueMax, operator of the Bendemeer Center branch and 15 like it in Singapore, plans to expand not only into neighboring Malaysia - where it has four branches - but also beyond Asia, says ValueMax chief executive Yeah Lee Ching.
The company will fund it using 60 percent of the SGD 66 million it raised on the Singapore Stock Exchange this week.
While some discount lenders have come under fire for high interest rates, Ms Yeah says the mortgage not only offers lower rates than other lenders, but it also doesn&#39;t directly increase debt.
&quot;Customers are pawning items they already own, and cashing in on personal property doesn&#39;t add to household debt,&quot; he says.
In society, asset pledge is increasingly accepted as a means of providing short-term, secure financing.
Moreover, among those who use pawnshops are not only people in financial distress.
Wealthy Singaporeans also use ValueMax branches when they drop in gold bars or Rolex watches and can get up to 60 percent of the purchase price in cash.
Our customers come from all possible backgrounds.
&quot;These include wealthy individuals who need short-term borrowing for their bold deals or investments, or small businesses who need help solving their cash flow problems,&quot; says Ms Yeah.
Sometimes they just need money as fast as possible.
