Another day, another independence horror story.
This time there is a warning that a condition for an independent Scotland&#39;s membership in the EU would be its entry into Schengen.
This gave rise to stories of passport controls in Berwick and barbed wire along Hadrian&#39;s Wall.
It is true that the Strathclyde paper did mention the possible economic benefits of free movement with the rest of Europe, but – predictably – this did not make the headlines.
Also, no one has mentioned that EU member states spend a lot of time adapting their official laws if it suits them.
With Scotland now not in Schengen, an offer of continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession to Brussels in return for whatever they really want from the Scots.
So it&#39;s a pretty weak story.
And, moreover, so old that it became an excavation. I heard the journalistic duck that &quot;independence means passport controls&quot; at least 40 years ago.
Nevertheless, there is an interesting idea hidden in this bearded tale.
Why should an independent Scotland even be expected to listen to Europe?
Why trade London&#39;s grip for Brussels&#39;, especially now?
This is the real European story: the great post-war plan to unify Europe has finally failed.
Due to the euro crisis, the so-called Project Europe is officially dead.
Across Europe, parties devoted to resistance to the EU or the abolition of the euro as a common currency are gaining influence.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic party Alternative for Germany - founded this year - came seemingly out of nowhere and already captured almost five million votes in the September federal election, essentially &quot;sweeping&quot; the Free Democrats (equivalent to the British Liberal Democrats) out of the Bundestag.
There has always been resistance at home to the plan to create a federal Europe.
However, the current economic crisis has become a decisive moment.
Austerity dictated by Germany and the European Central Bank, together with the straitjacket placed on national economies through clinging to a single currency, have led many to believe that the European project has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments running high budget deficits – this was only true in the case of Greece.
Rather, it is a euro system that locks its members into exchange rates favorable to German exporters – and that is what German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the domestic currency, Southern Europe has a disadvantage in terms of domestic production compared to Germany.
The only help is to cut income and public spending - which Germany encourages.
Behind the current budget and currency problems is a deeper cause of Europe&#39;s lackluster performance.
As a result of Brussels-backed &quot;green&quot; energy policies -- code for supporting French and German firms at the expense of consumers -- European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gasoline as it does in the United States.
This is a crippling cost disadvantage, as we have already seen with Grangemouth.
Not even all the wage freezes in the world would prevent Europe&#39;s petrochemical industry from being trampled by cheap US shale oil.
The result is a smoldering rebellion, especially in France, once an enthusiastic supporter of the EU.
After the war, the political elite in France saw the EU as a tool to keep Germany in check and allow Paris to position itself in the world on a par with Washington.
