Karel Drábek: Uhlířský vrch - one of our youngest volcanoes.
Uhlířský vrch is a striking hill 3 km southeast of Bruntál.
Along with several others, it is evidence of volcanic activity in Nízké Jeseník in recent times (from a geological point of view).
The last eruptions here were at the beginning of the Quaternary.
When viewed from a greater distance, on the top of Uhlířský vrch, the white-plastered baroque pilgrimage church of Our Lady of Help, built between 1755 and 1765, is striking.
It replaced the original wooden pilgrimage chapel.
The inn that stood next to the church has not survived.
Shortly after the completion of the church, an avenue of four rows of linden trees, about 1 km long, was planted.
The Stations of the Cross on Uhlířský vrch is already the third version, the original one stood here after 1916, the second, from 2001, lasted only until 2004.
At fifteen stops there are wooden sculptures made by the local artistic carver František Nedomlel.
He used various types of wood from the Nízké Jeseník region.
Similarly, plinths made of rocks from the local area form an interesting geological exposition.
The name of the sponsor is also indicated at each stop.
Uhlířský vrch is the remnant of a young volcano.
Although data from radiometric age measurements vary somewhat, the last eruption here was about 1.5 million years ago.
It is therefore younger than the Great Roudny (3.3 million years old) and older than the Venus volcano (0.8 million years old).
The volcano was born from an explosion.
During it, it ejected a considerable amount of volcanic ash together with rock fragments from the bedrock, which were burnt to a reddish-brown color.
At the end of this phase, lava flowed to the surface - today it is a layer of porous basalt up to 13 meters thick.
The second eruption spewed out red, brown-red, and in some places even black tuffs.
Their layer is up to 50 meters thick and part of it is accessible in the quarry wall.
In the tuffs there are conspicuous volcanic pumas up to 1 meter in size. The second eruption was also ended by an outpouring of lava.
At the end of the activity, lava flowed out of the volcano, which today forms a layer of slag-like basalt up to 50 m thick.
Volcanoes that alternate between ejecting volcanic ash and lava flows are the most common type of volcano.
Because they are actually composed of layers, they are called stratovolcanoes.
The original volcanic cone was gradually eroded.
However, it was only threatened by the mining of rocks in the quarry on the south side.
The most intensive mining took place here in the years 1953 - 1962.
Tuffs were added to concrete, which was then lighter and had better thermal insulation properties.
Mining was stopped under pressure from experts and the public, thus preserving this unique place.
The problem, however, is the porosity and low cohesion of the rocks, which quickly weather, disintegrate and slide down the slope.
The quarry thus disappears relatively quickly.
To further complicate the situation, the warm, south-facing slope is an ideal location for some rare species of plants and animals.
The remedy is therefore problematic, but over time it will be necessary to select and maintain a characteristic geological profile.
This is nothing new, similar profiles are maintained on a number of important sites.
You can reach Uhlířský vrch by following the green tourist sign from Bruntál or from Slezské Kočov.
Motorists can use the free parking lot at the beginning of the linden avenue, where a short educational trail also begins.
