Scientists shed more light on how tail movements are related to a dog&#39;s mood
Previous research has shown that happy dogs wag their tails more to the right (from the dog&#39;s point of view), while nervous dogs wag their tails more to the left.
But now scientists say that other dogs can pick up on and respond to these subtle differences in tail movement.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neurobiologist at the University of Trento, said: &quot;In humans, it is well known that the left and right sides of the brain have different connections to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions.&quot;
We tried to observe the same thing in other species.
He added that, just as in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain is responsible for left-handed movements and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres play different roles in emotions.
In an attempt to learn more about how dogs respond to other dogs&#39; disproportionate tail wagging, researchers monitored animals watching movies about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of these animals and analyzed their behavior.
It probably won&#39;t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and other times to the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: &quot;We showed the dogs movies of dogs - either in the natural version or in silhouette - to get rid of any confounding cues, and we were also able to adjust the tail movement to make it appear more to the right or to the left.&quot;
When the animals saw the otherwise inconspicuous dog move its tail to the right (from the perspective of the tail-wagging dog), it remained completely still.
But when she noticed the tail turning predominantly to the left (again from the point of view of the tail-wagging dog), their heart rates increased and the animals appeared uncertain.
Professor Vallortigara said he did not think the dogs consciously communicated with each other through these movements.
Rather, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they need to pay attention to and which they don&#39;t need to pay attention to.
He said: &quot;If you encounter dogs several times and moving their tail in one direction is repeatedly associated with more friendly behavior and moving to the right produces less friendly behavior, you will respond based on that experience.&quot;
The researchers say the findings may help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers better understand their animals&#39; emotions.
Dog behaviourist John Bradshaw, an undergraduate lecturer in veterinary medicine at the University of Bristol, said this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right sides were important to dogs.
Last year, a team from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when observing an aggressive dog and to the right when looking at a happy dog.
And in another paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he said: &quot;Dogs were more likely to become familiar with the dog robot when it wagged its tail to the left than to the right, when it was more likely to become uncertain - exactly the opposite of the Italian study.&quot;
The difference, he says, may be due to the fact that the dogs in these various studies did not interpret the animals in the movies or the dog robots as completely dogs.
He explained that studies of how dogs react to real dogs could help.
&quot;Although there is strong evidence in many different mammals that the two sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be elucidated – and dogs are no exception,&quot; he said.
But given how easy it is to record their behavior, it probably won&#39;t be long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes to one side and sometimes to the other.
RBS suspends two foreign currency traders
Royal Bank of Scotland (RBS) is suspending two traders in its foreign exchange division, according to two people familiar with the situation, in another sign that global probes by regulators into suspected currency market manipulation are on the rise.
Some of the world&#39;s biggest banks, including UBS, Barclays, Deutsche Bank and RBS, have confirmed they are cooperating with competent authorities in investigations into the world&#39;s largest financial market, where $5.3 trillion changes hands every day.
