The bank declined to comment on the suspension but confirmed it had received a request for information from the authorities this month.
&quot;Our ongoing investigation into this matter continues and we are fully cooperating with the FCA and our other authorities,&quot; the bank said two weeks ago.
Last month, people close to the matter said RBS handed over to Britain&#39;s Financial Conduct Authority records of emails and instant messages sent from and to the former trader&#39;s accounts.
That trader, Richard Usher, left RBS in 2010 and is understood to have been relieved of his current position as European head of foreign exchange trading at JPMorgan.
Rohan Ramchandani, European head of cash trading at Citi, went on leave this week, while Matt Gardiner, former head of currency trading at Barclays and UBS, was suspended by Standard Chartered this week.
Neither of these traders has been charged with any wrongdoing.
Mr. Usher&#39;s instant messaging group included bankers from Barclays and Citigroup, people familiar with the matter said.
UBS said this week it had taken action against some of its employees after Swiss watchdog Finma said it was investigating suspected foreign exchange manipulation at several Swiss banks.
Globally, at least six authorities - the European Commission, Finma, Swiss antitrust authority Weko, the FCA, the US Department of Justice and the Hong Kong Monetary Authority - are investigating claims that these bankers colluded to manipulate the currency market.
In addition, HSBC, Citigroup, JPMorgan and Credit Suisse have launched internal investigations or received requests for information from authorities, people familiar with the situation said.
Banks comb through years-old instant messages and emails to find instances of wrongdoing.
News of the investigations alarmed traders in a sector that has been one of the biggest engines of profit-making at investment bank closes in recent years, but which has been disrupted as little currency volatility has limited opportunities for speculators.
Some bankers have tried to play down the gravity of the situation by saying that the vast and highly liquid foreign exchange market is essentially impossible to manipulate, but senior traders say that is not necessarily true.
A senior trader said that despite the significant volume of daily forex trading, the fragmentation of liquidity between different trading platforms and banks increasing the use of their own internal platforms means that &quot;you can start to influence the market at relatively low prices.&quot;
The news came on the same day that Credit Suisse said it had this week fired a trader from its equity trading division who caused a loss of nearly $6 million late last year.
The bank immediately alerted the relevant authorities and is cooperating with their control bodies.
&quot;We are confident that this trader acted alone and that this issue has been resolved,&quot; Credit Suisse said.
