The royal commission has heard that two staff members of the Young Men&#39;s Christian Association (YMCA) were accused before the charges against Jonathan Lord
The Royal Commission into Child Sexual Abuse has heard that before charges were laid against Caringbah child educator Jonathan Lord in 2011, two New South Wales Young Men&#39;s Christian Association (YMCA) staff were accused of child sexual abuse.
But it was heard before the commission that in its opening statement to the commission, the association said that they had never dealt with a case of child sexual abuse in their organization.
Chief executive Phillip Hare was asked about a case in which a YMCA staff member was charged with child pornography offenses and another in which a Caringbah YMCA trainer was convicted in 1991 of sexually abusing children in his care .
Mr Hare told Gail Furness, an adviser to the commission, that he knew about the first case but not the second.
He admitted that the YMCA&#39;s initial statement was also inaccurate when it said there had been external audits of the YMCA that recognized the organization as a leading advocate for children&#39;s rights.
Evidence presented by the commission said the YMCA was made aware that it had received the second-lowest of four possible ratings in a Department for Education and Society audit in August this year.
Mr Hare, who started working with the YMCA when he was 21, admitted management from himself down failed to take Mr Lord on without making sure staff were aware of their duty to report breaches of child safety rules.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sexually assaulting 12 boys during a two-year stint at the YMCA.
He was jailed for a minimum of six years.
But Mr Hare rejected claims the YMCA had a cultural problem which prevented staff from reporting Mr Lord&#39;s breach of child safety.
Staff members gave evidence that they witnessed such violations, including Lord being alone with the children, privately watching them, letting them sit on his lap, telling them he loved them, and letting them play with his cellphone by phone.
Danielle Ockwell, who was Lord&#39;s subordinate and requested child safety training because she was concerned about his behaviour, testified that Jacqui Barnat, head of children&#39;s services at the YMCA in Caringbah, who was Lord&#39;s supervisor, was &quot;very intimidating and often hard to talk to him about anything&quot;.
The CEO said he did not accept staff&#39;s evidence that they felt uncomfortable contacting their superiors to report the incidents.
Instead, he said their friendship with Lorde clouded their judgment and that&#39;s why they didn&#39;t report the problem.
Mr Hare said he told the New South Wales YMCA board his view that the lesson for the organization from the &quot;Jonathan Lord case&quot; was that staff &quot;didn&#39;t report back&quot;, and the board agreed with him.
Mr Hare said the decision to have staff sign non-disclosure agreements was made by the YMCA&#39;s general manager of children&#39;s services, Liam Whitley, shortly after the allegations emerged.
He said the aim was to avoid tampering with evidence but was &quot;overzealous&quot; and poorly executed.
Child sexual abuse expert Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University told the commission the NSW YMCA was not a child-safe organization between 2009 and 2011.
He said there were serious problems with recruitment, screening, onboarding, training and management of staff.
The hearing was adjourned until December 20.
