FAA: Airline passengers can now use tech on planes (but not make calls from their cell phones)
Airline passengers will be able to use their electronic devices &quot;gate-to-gate&quot; — in addition to making calls from their cellphones — to read, play games, watch movies and listen to music under eagerly awaited new rules issued Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA ).
However, passengers should not expect changes to occur immediately.
How quickly the change will be implemented will vary by airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a news conference.
Airlines will have to demonstrate to the FAA that their airplanes comply with the new rules and that they have updated cabin crew training manuals and equipment stowage guidelines to comply with the new rules.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices on planes.
Among the companies that have already submitted plans are Delta and JetBlue.
&quot;Depending on the status of such a plan, we can improve the expanded use of electronic devices very quickly,&quot; the FAA said in a statement.
Passengers are currently required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the aircraft doors close.
They cannot turn them on until the plane reaches an altitude of 3 kilometers and the captain gives permission.
Passengers are expected to turn their devices off again when the plane is descending to land and not to turn them back on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new rules, airlines whose planes are properly shielded against electronic interference can allow their passengers to use their devices during takeoff, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft that have been modified to allow passengers to use Wifi at higher altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the Association of Professional Stewards, welcomed the changes.
&quot;Once the new rules are safely in place - and we will be working closely with the transport companies on this - it will be a success,&quot; Glading said in a statement.
Frankly speaking, we are getting tired of looking like &quot;watchmen&quot;.
However, surfing the Internet, sending e-mails and SMS or downloading data will continue to be prohibited below 3 kilometers above sea level, the agency said.
Passengers will be notified to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
So still no Words with friends, the online scrabble game actor Alec Baldwin was playing on his smartphone in 2011 when he was famously kicked off an American Airlines flight for refusing to turn off his device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And heavier devices such as laptops will still have to be stored due to concerns they could injure someone if they fly around the cabin.
Cell phone calls will continue to be prohibited on board.
The rules for cell phone use are not set by the FAA, but by the US Federal Telecommunications Commission.
The FAA may lift the ban on certain electronic devices during takeoff and landing.
Last month, Mark Rosenker of the State Transportation Safety Board, an expert on national transportation safety for CBS News, said cellphones continue to be considered a risk.
&quot;Cell phones are a real problem, not only because they can potentially create interference with navigation devices, but we also know from FCC data that they can cause interference to transmission towers in the air,&quot; Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee created by the FAA to study the issue suggested last month that the government allow the electronic devices to be used more widely.
The FAA has come under pressure in recent years to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Sen. Claire McCaskill, D-Missouri, say there is no legitimate security reason for the ban.
Restrictions are also increasingly difficult to enforce as the use of such devices becomes ubiquitous.
Some studies indicate that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore the obligation to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting the use of electronic devices by passengers in 1966 in response to interference with navigation and communications equipment when passengers began carrying FM radios, a technological achievement of the time.
The new airliners are much more reliant on electrical systems than previous generation aircraft, but they are also engineered and approved by the FAA to be immune to electronic interference.
Airlines have offered Wi-Fi to passengers at cruising altitudes for several years.
Plans tailored for Wi-Fi systems are also more resistant to interference.
The vast majority of airlines should adapt to greater use of electronic devices under the new rules, Huert said.
Today&#39;s electronic devices generally emit much less intense radio emissions than devices of previous generations.
E-readers, for example, emit only minimal emissions when turning a page.
But broadcasting is stronger when devices are downloading or sending data.
Among those pushing to loosen restrictions on passenger use of these devices is Amazon.com.
In 2011, representatives of this company loaded an airliner with their Kindle e-readers and conducted a test flight, but no problem appeared.
Members of the FAA&#39;s advisory board expressed mixed feelings about whether the devices pose any risks.
Douglas Kidd of the National Airline Passenger Association said he believes interference from these devices is real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there are only sketchy reports from pilots to support the fact that such devices can cause interference with aircraft systems, and most of those reports are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to order passengers to turn off their devices during low-visibility instrument flying.
A travel industry group has welcomed the changes, saying they are a sensible move for the traveling public, who make heavy use of technology.
&quot;We are pleased that the FAA has recognized that a pleasant travel experience does not conflict with safety,&quot; said Roger Dow, executive director of the American Travel Association.
In unprecedented admission, John Kerry says US spying &#39;has gone too far&#39;
John Kerry has signaled a softening of the US defense stance on its surveillance programs, saying in an unprecedented admission that in some cases the spying has &quot;gone too far&quot;.
