There will probably be police specialists in the ghettos, they are supposed to ease the tension
Police specialists should work in the ghettos in the Czech Republic in the future.
They would spend up to half of their errands here.
They would keep order and solve problems.
Thanks to their knowledge of the environment, they should contribute to reducing the tension between people from slums and residents from the surrounding area.
The Ministry of the Interior takes this into account in its proposal to reduce security risks.
According to him, &quot;accelerated provision of social housing&quot; would mainly help to improve the situation in the country.
The document was discussed by the government.
According to the analysis, there were around 300 poor houses and neighborhoods in the Czech Republic a few years ago.
80,000 people lived in them, mainly Roma.
Adults in the ghettos were jobless, families were dependent on benefits, children ended up in &quot;special&quot; schools.
Usury was rampant.
According to experts, problem locations have increased by a hundred in the meantime.
Relations between their inhabitants and others become strained.
Anti-Roma marches were held in several places.
People from the neighborhood also joined the extremists.
According to the interior, it is difficult for the police to maintain security and order in areas with ghettos.
A fundamental condition is said to be &quot;consistent application of an equal approach in law enforcement&quot;.
But this is said to be impossible to achieve without detailed knowledge of the place and people.
The specialist would go on errands in the ghetto, where he would spend up to half of his service, the rest he would serve in his district.
He would oversee order in a troubled locality.
He would also know the locals, so he would be better able to solve problems or offenses.
