Young Czechs know that they must save.
But most of them have no idea with what interest
More and more Czechs are saving money.
However, they do not reach the savings champions in the region.
Austrians save the most money, saving an average of 181 euros per month.
People in Slovakia also save a little more than the Czechs.
This follows from a survey by the Erste Savings Barometer group in the countries of Central and Eastern Europe.
It also showed that the mood of savers is improving and two-thirds of those surveyed plan to put more money away.
While Czechs are roughly in the middle of the ranking of savers, people in Romania and Serbia still use very little savings products.
For example, according to the survey, almost every second Serb saves money &quot;under the pillow&quot; at home.
In the country, the number of those who save higher amounts each month has increased this year.
As recently as last year, 26 percent of respondents saved between 1,000 and 2,500 crowns every month for various types of savings, this year it is five percent more.
However, the average monthly deposit fell slightly to 2,078 crowns in a year-on-year comparison.
The biggest hit among savings products is supplementary pension insurance.
This is preferred by 54 percent of Czechs, while three years ago it was the most popular way to evaluate savings for only 36 percent of people.
On the contrary, the popularity of building savings is decreasing, compared to last year, interest in investment funds has also fallen significantly.
Only 16 percent of respondents already use them, while last year it was almost a quarter of people.
The survey also showed that although people consider it important to save, most of them do not know what returns they achieve on individual products.
Above all, young people under the age of 30 do not know how their money earns interest.
On the contrary, the oldest group of respondents have the best awareness of the profitability of their saved money, among people over fifty years of age, 73 percent of the respondents know this.
In an international comparison of the Erste Group, Czechs lead in the use of online banking, which is regularly used by 44 percent of people.
They are followed by Slovaks and Austrians with a 12 percent gap.
