Six out of ten companies are preparing for the new Civil Code
Six companies out of ten are intensively preparing for the impending effect of the new Civil Code and the Act on Business Corporations from January 1, 2014.
Only eight percent of the interviewed company representatives said that they did not deal with matters related to both key codes in their company at all.
This follows from a survey by the law firm Ambruz &amp; Dark Deloitte Legal, which ascertained the opinions of 108 Czech companies.
In connection with the approaching effective date of both key codes, it is only now at the last minute that many managers are beginning to realize what a significant influence they can have on the business of their companies.
In our opinion, the biggest changes in private law in the last 50 years will affect all citizens and companies in the Czech Republic.
Due to the maneuvering of politicians, the business sector lived in uncertainty for a long time, whether revolutionary changes would eventually happen or not.
&quot;Now, however, they only have a few weeks left so that the transition to the new law can take place for their companies without complications,&quot; commented Ambruz &amp; Dark Deloitte Legal partner Jan Spáčil on the results.
Of the 61 percent of companies intensively dealing with the new codes, 26 percent said their companies have already taken all the necessary steps to be ready in time.
Furthermore, 35 percent of companies from this number are preparing to take the necessary measures in the near future.
On the other hand, every fifth company has not yet dealt with recodifications, but still has a concrete idea of how to prepare for them.
A total of 11 percent do not have an opinion and cannot assess the issue.
Only eight percent of companies admit that they have not yet dealt with issues related to recodifications.
The most important legal topic related to the new Civil Code for the largest number of surveyed companies is the conclusion of new contracts (21 percent), followed by the resolution of business terms and conditions (16 percent) and then changes in the real estate cadastre and liability for damage (ten percent each).
With contracts, one of the most significant innovations of the entire recodification will take place, namely the unification of the regulation of contracts only within the framework of the new Civil Code.
The current parallel regulation in the Civil Code and the Commercial Code will disappear, as a result of which contract law should become clearer for citizens and entrepreneurs.
&quot;In the case of entrepreneurs, the new regulation will offer many novelties with an emphasis on greater freedom in the arrangement of relationships,&quot; pointed out attorney Ambruz &amp; Dark Deloitte Legal Lukáš Poddaný.
In connection with the Law on Business Corporations, almost a quarter of companies consider the issue of increasing the responsibility of statutory bodies to be the most important topic.
This is followed by topics related to changes in convening and conducting the general meeting (15 percent) and company representation (14 percent).
The new legislation means stricter obligations and possible impacts for statutory bodies, especially in a situation where the company is at risk of bankruptcy or going into bankruptcy.
&quot;In practice, this means that if the members of the board of directors and company executives do not act with the care of a proper manager and do not avert the impending bankruptcy of the company, they may lose the benefit obtained for the performance of the function for the last two years,&quot; added Spáčil.
