At the behest of the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution (BfV), Germany&#39;s domestic intelligence agency, the purpose of the mission was to take photographs of the roof of a US outpost located less than 5 km from the European Central Bank and the Bundesbank.
German media say the BfV hoped to be able to identify the presence of eavesdropping antennas, and the action triggered an exchange of views between the US and German foreign ministers in Berlin.
James Clapper, the U.S. director of national intelligence, insisted again in September that the United States does not use its foreign intelligence capabilities &quot;to steal the trade secrets of foreign companies for the benefit of U.S. companies to strengthen their international competitiveness or increase their profits.&quot;
But since collaborator-turned-whistleblower Edward Snowden began to reveal his valuable collection of secret US surveillance, European governments and leading businessmen no longer know whether to trust the director&#39;s words.
Public paranoia about state surveillance has reached new heights following reports that the US National Security Agency spied on a Brazilian oil company and gained access to data held by US cloud providers including Google and Yahoo.
The final straw came with the revelation that Chancellor Angela Merkel&#39;s phone may have been tapped for a decade.
If the most powerful person in Europe can be a target, then surely leading businessmen are also potential targets.
Snowden has made transparent the intense cooperation between US intelligence services and companies.
I would say that it is possible that this data is being used for mutual benefit.
&quot;Germany needs to wake up,&quot; said Oliver Grün, president of BITMi, which represents small and medium-sized IT companies in Germany.
German companies believe the US now poses as much of a risk as China when it comes to industrial espionage and data theft, according to a survey released in July by consultancy EY.
But so far there is no evidence in the entire dossier revealed by Mr. Snowden that the United States has passed on the trade secrets of foreign firms to its own companies.
Politicians have expressed concern that the EU lacks certain IT and internet capabilities and said it should seek to reduce its dependence on the US:
Leading entrepreneurs are skeptical about it.
Voices are coming from the German parliament that we should make a German Google.
I can only close my eyes and slowly open them again...
That&#39;s not the way to go, says Hasso Plattner, chairman of German software company SAP.
If someone wanted a strong European IT industry, they should not have let it die 20 years ago.
Everything in Germany is subsidized, from coal to cars to farmers.
Everything except the IT industry.
The scope and technical sophistication of US spy agencies revealed by Snowden is still shocking to some companies, which until now believed that China posed the biggest threat from surveillance.
There is a major shift in cloud computing where European officials have become increasingly aware that data stored in the US falls under US jurisdiction and is therefore potentially subject to attack.
About 10 percent of non-US members canceled plans to use a US-based cloud provider after the US Prism data-mining program was exposed, according to a survey by the Cloud security alliance.
Jim Snabe, one of SAP&#39;s CEOs, says: &quot;We have this new question for customers that wasn&#39;t there a year ago - where is my data stored and can you guarantee that it will physically stay in that jurisdiction?&quot;
Many senior German officials argue that the latest news is just confirmation of what they already knew: that powerful states want to steal their most valuable secrets, and this data must be protected at all costs.
That economic espionage is carried out is no surprise.
It always happened.
&quot;It&#39;s been a fundamental topic for many years and it hasn&#39;t changed significantly even during the current discussion,&quot; says Kurt Bock, CEO of the agrochemical company BASF.
Americans spy on us on a commercial and industrial level, just as we spy on them because it is in our national interest to defend our businesses.
Business leaders generally don&#39;t want to brag about the countermeasures they&#39;ve taken, lest they give an attacker an advantage.
In the case of large companies, it has long been reminded that taking a free USB memory stick to a trade fair or leaving an unprotected laptop in a hotel room is at least unreasonable.
Audi board member Ulrich Hackenberg says it has been common practice for many years to collect mobile phones before board meetings to prevent them from being used as eavesdropping devices.
Germany&#39;s BfV advises executives to consider not using simple prepaid mobile phones when traveling abroad due to the risk that smartphones can be stolen.
Prepaid cell phones are then thrown away.
However, there is concern that SMEs will remain vulnerable to hacking and surveillance.
In Germany, many of these companies are global market leaders in their specific fields.
&quot;SMEs often lack the experience, personnel and financial resources to effectively protect company secrets against unauthorized access,&quot; the BfV warns in its report.
The US warns its own companies against economic espionage by other countries.
According to the Washington Post, US National Intelligence Estimates in February listed France as the second-ranked perpetrator behind China in hacking economic news, alongside Russia and Israel.
A board member at a German risk-free company concluded that &quot;the French are the worst&quot; when it comes to economic espionage.
Bernard Squarcini, the former head of France&#39;s domestic intelligence agency DCRI, said in an interview this month: &quot;The services know very well that all countries, even if they cooperate in the fight against terrorism, are spying on their allies.&quot;
A new nicotine vaccine may take the pleasure out of smoking
Scientists have developed a nicotine vaccine that can take the pleasure out of smoking a cigarette.
A single dose of the vaccine was able to protect a mouse from nicotine addiction for life.
More tests are needed and will take several years before human trials, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell Medical School in New York says early signs are good.
&quot;We strongly hope that this kind of vaccination strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit and have exhausted all the methods available on the market today, only to find that their nicotine addiction is so strong that it can overcome all current approaches,&quot; he said. Professor Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been engineered to carry the genetic information to make anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of these antibodies.
The antibodies chase down any nicotine molecules in the bloodstream and neutralize them before they reach the brain, preventing the smoker from getting a nicotine hit.
In tests, vaccinated mice that were additionally given nicotine continued their normal activities.
But the mice that weren&#39;t vaccinated &quot;calmed down,&quot; the researchers said, a sign that the nicotine had entered their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The injections had to be given so often to maintain sufficient levels of antibodies, so they proved expensive and impractical.
The cost of the new vaccine should be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if future vaccines were completely safe for humans, they could be given to children before they have the urge to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
However, it would be much more likely to be used by smokers to quit.
&quot;They&#39;ll know that if they start smoking again, because of the nicotine vaccine, they won&#39;t get any benefit from it, and that will help them kick the habit,&quot; he said.
British researchers said the results were interesting, but cautioned that more research is needed.
The desperate cry of an Obama voter
I voted for Obama twice - I shared the hope for possible change
He says Obama&#39;s sincere efforts were thwarted by GOP obstruction
Obstructive politics cannot excuse the woes of Obama&#39;s health care website or drone attacks
Obama&#39;s 2008 campaign memoir is a sad reminder of what might have happened
Nathaniel P. Morris is in his second year studying medicine at Harvard.
I am reading a very sad book these days.
I thought this book would cheer me up and restore a glimmer of hope during the dark days of my second year of medical school.
It&#39;s called &quot;The Audacity to Win&quot; and it&#39;s about memories of Barack Obama&#39;s 2008 presidential campaign.
When I finish the patient reviews and go to bed in the evening, the book takes me back to a time when politics inspired millions and speeches took your breath away.
The election ended in a landslide and the television coverage made us think about the historical value of this moment.
My classmates were crying with joy and my parents were hiding the newspapers they found.
A young team of visionaries headed to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
During the 2008 inauguration, Obama had an 82 percent approval rating.
And here I close the book.
Moving into the present is a rude awakening, like waking up from a dream.
It&#39;s hard to remember those optimistic days—they seem like distant memories, a sad reminder of missed opportunities.
In the years since I cast my first ballot, things have indeed changed.
It was definitely nothing like I imagined.
I recognize that Obama has achieved a number of great and varied accomplishments—from the Affordable Care Act to the withdrawal of our troops from Iraq and the end of the &quot;don&#39;t ask, don&#39;t tell&quot; policy after the killing of Osama bin Laden.
Moreover, I believe that partisan obstruction has derailed so many efforts to move our nation forward: immigration reform, public health care options, and closing Guantánamo Bay, among others.
But after many times defending the Obama administration in front of colleagues and friends, I have reached an absolute limit as to the explanations they can provide.
I found myself in a place of political hopelessness.
Republican obstructionism cannot explain consent to eavesdropping on foreign leaders or drone strikes that kill innocent children overseas.
They cannot explain the National Security Agency collecting data on the private lives of Americans, nor that it persecutes those who expose government wrongdoing.
They cannot be held responsible for the execution of Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, without a proper trial, or for limiting public contributions and spending during presidential campaigns.
They cannot justify the report&#39;s finding that the White House&#39;s efforts to silence the media are &quot;the most aggressive ... since the Nixon administration.&quot;
And most recently, they can&#39;t even excuse the inability to create a simple website more than 3 years after the Affordable Care Act was signed.
I don&#39;t know if something like this could have been expected.
Whether I should have guessed at 18 that government power could be at odds with the political campaigns that preceded it.
Elected office obviously has no predictable course, and our public conversations will be shaped by the opposing political party and random events like the Newton massacre.
However, all of the examples I have given above seem to be largely the result of the administration&#39;s own decision.
And that bothers me the most.
I voted for Obama again in 2012, but not because I was excited about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney presented a confused and unpolished alternative and seemed unable to solidify his policies or position.
I had a feeling that a second term for Obama, freed from the pressure of the next election, would fulfill the hopes we once heard about.
Still, going back to 2008 -- with Obama&#39;s approval rating dipping below 45% this week -- is getting harder and harder through this book.
It makes me remember the many promises that have been lost.
This week I read a chapter in a book about Obama&#39;s crushing defeat to Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
In a follow-up meeting during the campaign, he told his staff that he needed to get back on track and stay true to his mission.
&quot;I want our magic back,&quot; he said.
We must not forget who we are.
It&#39;s been five years, Mr. President, and I totally agree with you.
The views expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
