Syria destroyed its chemical weapons production facilities, watchdog says
Syria has destroyed critical equipment for the production of chemical weapons and poison gas munitions, the global chemical weapons watchdog said on Thursday, as fierce fighting erupted in the country&#39;s north, not far from one of the sites believed to contain the poison.
Also on Thursday, a Syrian activist group said more than 120,000 residents had been killed since the civil war began nearly three years ago.
The announcement by the Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons came the day before November 1,
a deadline the Hague-based organization set for Damascus to destroy or disable all chemical weapons production facilities and machinery for mixing chemicals to create poison gas and fill ammunition.
The completion of this essentially initial phase of destruction is a significant milestone in the ambitious timetable that aims to destroy all of Damascus&#39; chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of the equipment means that Syria will no longer be able to produce new chemical weapons.
However, Damascus has yet to begin destroying existing weapons and stockpiles.
The country is believed to have about 1,000 tons of chemicals and weapons, including mustard gas and sarin nerve gas.
The announcement came as fighting raged on Thursday in the town of Safira, which experts say is home to a chemical weapons factory and storage facilities, the Britain-based Syrian Observatory for Human Rights said.
An activist group monitoring the overall death toll through the Syria Activist Network reported on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 are to be civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, there are supposed to be 29,954 members of Bashar Assad&#39;s armed forces, 18,678 pro-government fighters and 187 militants from the Lebanese Hezbollah.
The dead are also said to include 2,202 government defectors and approximately 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
On 25 July, the United Nations estimated that 100,000 people had died in the conflict since March 2011.
This number has not been updated since then.
The conflict has forced about 2 million residents to flee the country.
Assad&#39;s forces have been fighting in Safirah against insurgents, many of whom are linked to al-Qaeda, for weeks.
The Observatory said on Thursday that there were casualties on both sides, but did not have specific numbers.
The fighting has underscored the dangers facing chemical weapons inspectors, who face tight deadlines in their mission to rid Syria of its chemical arsenal amid an ongoing civil war.
A statement from the OPCW, which works closely with the UN, said its team was now &quot;satisfied to have verified - and monitored the destruction of - Syria&#39;s declared critical production and mixing/filling equipment&quot;.
He added that &quot;no further control activities are currently planned&quot;.
Earlier this week, inspectors said they had completed the first round of verification work, visiting 21 of the 23 sites declared by Damascus.
Inspectors said they were unable to visit two sites due to safety concerns.
On Thursday, the OPCW said the two sites had been &quot;abandoned and ... items of the chemical weapons program they contained were moved to two other declared sites that were inspected,&quot; according to Syria.
It was not immediately clear whether the Safira facility was one of the sites OPCW inspectors could not visit.
Syria has agreed to a plan to completely destroy its chemical weapons, which must be approved by the OPCW&#39;s executive committee next month.
&quot;I bow to the courage and bravery you have shown in fulfilling this most challenging mission this organization has ever had,&quot; said Observer Director Ahmet Uzumcu in comments released by the OPCW.
Now in its third year, the civil war pits mainly Sunni Muslim rebels against Assad&#39;s government and its security forces, which are filled with members of the Alawite sect, an offshoot of Shiite Islam.
As for further developments, the head of the Observatory, Ramí Abdul Rahman, said that on Wednesday there was a strong explosion inside an air defense facility in Syria&#39;s coastal province of Lazikiya.
He said the cause of the blast was unknown.
