Early Puberty: Matures earlier
Research has shown that African-American and Hispanic girls reach puberty earlier than their Caucasian peers.
Physical changes do not mean puberty is approaching
Hormones or other chemicals have not been proven to be responsible
Experts say one of the triggers for earlier puberty may be the obesity epidemic.
The trend of earlier puberty is not as evident in boys.
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist who specializes in children&#39;s health and family issues.
Should a mother be alarmed when her daughter starts growing breasts and pubic hair at age 7 or 8?
At the American Academy of Pediatrics annual conference this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these physical changes are relatively common among American girls and represent a new standard.
&quot;I spent a lot of time reassuring parents that this is usually not a sign of rapid progress toward full puberty,&quot; Kaplowitz said.
Visible signs of development such as breast growth, pubic and armpit hair, and body odor appear earlier in girls.
However, there has been little change in the age at which the first period occurs over the past forty years.
In the United States, the median age is now 12.5 years, up from 12.75 in 1970.
&quot;Once breasts begin to develop, it&#39;s at least two to three years before the first period occurs,&quot; said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of &quot;Early puberty in girls: The Essential Guide to Coping with This Common Problem.&quot; : An essential guide to dealing with this common problem)
The most reliable test of how puberty will continue is time.
What triggers the actual onset of puberty is debated, but if breast growth is accompanied by a growth spurt before age 8, the girl is considered &quot;precocious&quot;.
In most cases, the process slows down or stops – which can be closely monitored by pediatricians.
Faster growth may be a reason for an endocrinologist to run tests to rule out serious problems, such as a tumor or cyst.
There are treatments that delay early menstruation and prevent other consequences: premature aging of the bones, which can eventually lead to stunting and stunting in adulthood.
Medication and hormone therapy recommendations are dependent on the child&#39;s age, developmental rate, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
Psychosociological aspects are also important.
When it comes to the use of medication, Kaplowitz is cautious, but acknowledges that &quot;suppressing puberty can alleviate problems with a girl&#39;s behavior and her feelings of being different from her peers.&quot;
Another big problem is understandable: Parents simply don&#39;t want their very young daughters to menstruate.
&quot;They&#39;re worried that she might get pregnant or how she&#39;s going to handle hygiene,&quot; Kaplowitz said.
&quot;It was a shock,&quot; recalls one woman whose daughter started menstruating at age 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about menstruation, she was not ready emotionally.
She came home from school scared and angry that she was the first of her friends.
There are many well-known theories about the causes of precocious puberty.
However, there is not yet a consistent body of evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
Boys - like girls - reach puberty earlier.
Kaplowitz advocates the assumption that the most serious reason is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of 6- to 9-year-old girls linking body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other findings support this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African-American and Hispanic girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their Caucasian counterparts.
The explanations are different.
From a global perspective, patterns of early puberty appear to be influenced by everything from economic conditions to climate to genes.
Another conundrum: Although boys begin to develop facial and pubic hair at an early age, the trend toward full bloom at early puberty is not as pronounced as it is for girls.
Other doctors attending the American Association of Pediatrics (AAP) conference added further complexity to the topic.
Acne and pubic hair are common even in infants and toddlers.
&quot;We have to be careful about how we identify the true onset of puberty,&quot; said Lawrence Silverman, a pediatric endocrinologist at Goryeb Children&#39;s Hospital in Morristown, New Jersey.
Parents should not hesitate to get guidance from their pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
&quot;It may mean having to talk to the child sooner than you think,&quot; advised Kaplowitz.
If you stay calm, your child will likely respond well.
Girls who develop earlier need reassurance that even if it happens prematurely, this process is a normal part of life.
