Bombardier&#39;s profit plunged as deliveries and orders fell
Canadian plane and train maker Bombardier reported a 15 percent drop in net profit on Thursday, driven by fewer aircraft orders and deliveries in the third quarter and contractual issues in its train unit.
Montreal-based Bombardier also did not release any flight test data for its new CSeries jet, nor did it offer an update on whether the plane will follow through on an ambitious plan to enter commercial service next September.
After the initial test flight about a month and a half ago, the plane has only flown three times, raising questions about whether the testing phase is progressing well.
The results missed estimates and shares fell 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
State Bank analyst Cameron Doerksen downgraded the stock from &quot;outperform&quot; to &quot;sector perform&quot; on Thursday, expecting the stock to experience limited growth over the next quarter or two.
&quot;While we were mostly expecting lower aircraft deliveries, the profit margin in the transportation business disappointed us significantly,&quot; Doerksen said in a note to clients.
As the test program continues, we believe Bombardier will receive new orders for the CSeries aircraft.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect market skepticism towards the program to grow.
Bombardier hopes the CSeries aircraft will make inroads into the lower end of the market, now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first test aircraft was unveiled in March, and after a delay of several months, the first flight took place in September.
However, the number of firm orders for the CSeries aircraft stands at a modest 177 as potential buyers await test flight results to verify the company&#39;s claims of low fuel consumption and cost savings for the airliner.
There are currently a total of 403 orders and commitments from 15 customers and operators.
Chief executive Pierre Beaudoin expected Bombardier to reach its target of 300 firm orders when the first aircraft entered commercial service.
Executives also assured analysts and the media on Thursday that the program was proceeding according to plan.
&quot;The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected,&quot; Beaudoin said in a conference call, noting that ground checks and software updates were scheduled during the aircraft&#39;s downtime.
Each manufacturer plans them differently.
We decided to do the first flight and then focus on the updates and that&#39;s what we did.
This will happen throughout the flight program.
According to Bombardier, the second of the five test aircraft should take off in the coming weeks, with the others not long after.
Still, analysts are skeptical that the first customer could begin operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier says it has been evaluating its plan to bring the aircraft into service and will provide updated information in the coming months.
&quot;This slow pace of flight testing – while consistent with Bombardier&#39;s internal schedule – appears to reinforce our view that commissioning will be pushed back to the first quarter of 2015,&quot; Doerksen said.
Bombardier&#39;s net income fell to $147 million, or 8 cents a share, in the third quarter ended Sept. 30, from $172 million, or 9 cents a share, a year earlier.
Adjusted earnings per share were flat at 9 cents.
Turnover fell marginally from $4.2 billion to $4.1 billion.
Analysts had expected earnings of 10 cents per share on revenue of 4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters&#39; IBES system.
The fourth-largest plane maker said it delivered just 45 planes during the quarter, down from 57 a year earlier.
Net orders fell from 83 aircraft to 26.
Unfulfilled orders in the aviation division amounted to 32.9 billion as of September 30, which did not change as of December 31.
&quot;Aeronautical results were in line with our outlook, but we were disappointed by low order intake and overall market conditions,&quot; Beaudoin said.
Revenue in the aerospace industry fell 13 percent to $2 billion.
Bombardier, the world&#39;s largest train maker, said revenue at the division rose nearly 11 percent to $2.1 billion.
Unfulfilled orders in transport amounted to 32.6 billion as of September 30, which is a marginal increase compared to December 31.
The profit margin in the transport division was affected by problems with the implementation of several large contracts.
Executives said a new outlook would be provided in the fourth quarter.
Shares in Bombardier, which also announced the arrival of Google CFO Patrick Pichette, fell 8.5 percent to $4.83 in afternoon trading on Thursday.
Brazil&#39;s Embraer SA, the third-largest maker of commercial aircraft and Bombardier&#39;s closest competitor, reported a 10 percent drop in quarterly profit on Thursday.
